The '''field sparrow''' ('''''Spizella pusilla''''') is a small [[American sparrow|New World sparrow]] in the [[family (taxonomy)|family]] [[Passerellidae]]. It is about {{convert|140|mm|in|0|abbr=on}} long and weighs about {{convert|12.5|g|oz|1|abbr=on}}. The head is grey with a rust-coloured crown, white eye-ring and pink bill. The upper parts are brown streaked with black and buff, the breast is buff, the belly is white and the tail is forked. There are two different colour [[Polymorphism (biology)|morphs]], one being greyer and the other more rufous.

The field sparrow is distributed across eastern Canada and the eastern United States, with northern populations migrating southwards to southern United States and north-eastern Mexico in the fall.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LLU8tgLU1uMC&pg=PA255 |page=255 |title=A Field Guide to Mexican Birds: Mexico, Guatemala, Belize, El Salvador |author1=Roger Tory Peterson |author2=Edward L. Chalif |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |year=1999 |isbn=978-0-395-97514-5 |access-date=2023-11-08 |archive-date=2023-11-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231108072318/https://books.google.com/books?id=LLU8tgLU1uMC&pg=PA255#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref> The typical habitat of this bird is bushy country with shrubs and grassland. The nest is a cup-shaped construction built on the ground and hidden beneath a bush or clump of grass. The birds forage on the ground or in low vegetation, feeding mainly on seeds and insects. The population is thought to be in slow decline, but it is a common species with a wide range, and the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has assessed its conservation status as being of "[[Least-concern species|least concern]]".

==Description==
Adults have brown upperparts, a buffy breast, a white belly, two whitish wing bars and a dark-brown forked tail. They have a grey face, a rusty crown, a white eye ring and a pink bill. They have rusty markings behind the eye. There are grey and [[rufous]] colour variants of the species.<ref name=BOC /><ref name=Sibley /> Males and females have a similar appearance with males being slightly larger than the females.<ref name="Biokids" />

